'''Lineage selection''', occurs when the frequency of one biological [[Lineage (evolution)|lineage]] changes in frequency relative to another lineage. Lineage selection is a generalization of individual based [[natural selection]]; the stating that an allele is favored by natural selection is equivalent to stating that the lineage bearing the allele is favored by natural selection.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Akçay|first=Erol|last2=Cleve|first2=Jeremy Van|date=2016-02-05|title=There is no fitness but fitness, and the lineage is its bearer|url=http://rstb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/371/1687/20150085|journal=Phil. Trans. R. Soc. B|language=en|volume=371|issue=1687|pages=20150085|doi=10.1098/rstb.2015.0085|issn=0962-8436|pmc=4760187|pmid=26729925}}</ref> For alleles with simple positive or negative fitness effects, lineage and individual based selection are equivalent. However, lineage selection can accommodate a wider array of evolutionary phenomena, such as the adaptive evolution of [[evolvability]], [[Altruism (biology)|altruism]], and [[Genetic recombination|recombination]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kirschner|first=Marc|last2=Gerhart|first2=John|date=1998-07-21|title=Evolvability|url=http://www.pnas.org/content/95/15/8420|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=95|issue=15|pages=8420–8427|issn=0027-8424|pmc=33871|pmid=9671692|doi=10.1073/pnas.95.15.8420}}</ref><ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Lineage Selection and the Maintenance of Sex|url=http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article/asset?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0066906.PDF|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=8 |issue=6e66906|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0066906|pages=e66906}}</ref> Additionally, lineage selection is useful in determining the effects of mutations in highly structured environments such as tumors.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nunney|first=Leonard|date=1999-03-07|title=Lineage selection and the evolution of multistage carcinogenesis|url=http://rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/266/1418/493|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|language=en|volume=266|issue=1418|pages=493–498|doi=10.1098/rspb.1999.0664|issn=0962-8452|pmc=1689794|pmid=10189713}}</ref>
